WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.200 --> 00:00:08.600
MALE SPEAKER: Good afternoon.

00:00:08.600 --> 00:00:13.310
Welcome to Musicians at Google
in Cambridge, Massachusetts.

00:00:13.310 --> 00:00:18.150
Please silence all cellphones,
real cutlery, anything

00:00:18.150 --> 00:00:21.210
that could make any noise.

00:00:21.210 --> 00:00:25.560
Thanks to David Flores, we
have a remarkable event today.

00:00:25.560 --> 00:00:29.930
I am here to introduce Brad
from Thinksay Records, who

00:00:29.930 --> 00:00:34.680
are releasing David Duchovny's
solo-- not solo album,

00:00:34.680 --> 00:00:36.640
it's recorded with a band.

00:00:36.640 --> 00:00:37.140
Sorry.

00:00:37.140 --> 00:00:38.420
First mistake already.

00:00:38.420 --> 00:00:39.700
He's chuckling.

00:00:39.700 --> 00:00:43.770
David Duchovny's new
album, "Hell or Highwater."

00:00:43.770 --> 00:00:47.100
We are the second audience
who will be hearing anything

00:00:47.100 --> 00:00:48.400
from this album.

00:00:48.400 --> 00:00:51.040
He's going to be playing
more from it tonight

00:00:51.040 --> 00:00:55.230
at Berkeley School of Music,
but they have to wait for us.

00:00:55.230 --> 00:00:58.560
So without further ado, let me
introduce Brad from Thinksay

00:00:58.560 --> 00:01:01.180
who's going to say some more.

00:01:01.180 --> 00:01:03.160
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:07.130 --> 00:01:09.580
BRAD: So I'm Brad
from Thinksay Records.

00:01:09.580 --> 00:01:13.610
We are located right here
in Boston, Massachusetts.

00:01:13.610 --> 00:01:17.490
And we are here today to
introduce David Duchovny.

00:01:17.490 --> 00:01:20.790
We want to thank him for
coming out here today--

00:01:20.790 --> 00:01:23.965
that'll be good,
thanks-- giving his time.

00:01:28.410 --> 00:01:30.440
We're a small
independent record label

00:01:30.440 --> 00:01:33.970
and we put out maybe like
one to three records a year.

00:01:33.970 --> 00:01:36.600
And through a mutual
friend over a year

00:01:36.600 --> 00:01:41.480
ago I was introduced to
David and he played me

00:01:41.480 --> 00:01:43.630
some of the songs that he wrote.

00:01:43.630 --> 00:01:45.590
And I really loved them.

00:01:45.590 --> 00:01:47.470
I thought the melodies
were really cool,

00:01:47.470 --> 00:01:51.551
and I thought lyrically
they were just like, wow.

00:01:51.551 --> 00:01:52.550
You could be a musician.

00:01:55.270 --> 00:01:57.790
And then we just
started talking,

00:01:57.790 --> 00:02:00.410
and we kind of vibed over
the same sort of stuff.

00:02:00.410 --> 00:02:04.990
And it became a
real project for me.

00:02:04.990 --> 00:02:06.790
The journey of
making this record

00:02:06.790 --> 00:02:10.050
was something when I
was in summer camp,

00:02:10.050 --> 00:02:13.890
and with Dave Flores, who
I was at summer camp with.

00:02:13.890 --> 00:02:17.590
And we would just listen to
records over and over again.

00:02:17.590 --> 00:02:20.150
And you'd be like,
oh, some day we're

00:02:20.150 --> 00:02:21.870
going to be in the
studio, and we're

00:02:21.870 --> 00:02:24.430
going to be making records.

00:02:24.430 --> 00:02:28.130
And that never, ever
happens, until, you know,

00:02:28.130 --> 00:02:30.080
I worked at Sony
Music for 20 years

00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:31.840
and I worked with
everybody from Beyonce

00:02:31.840 --> 00:02:33.550
to Johnny Cash to John Mayer.

00:02:33.550 --> 00:02:37.100
And it never happened until
this project came along

00:02:37.100 --> 00:02:40.700
that was just so niche and so
cool and so left of center.

00:02:40.700 --> 00:02:44.185
And I just entered on a
real journey with David

00:02:44.185 --> 00:02:46.900
and with everybody at
Thinksay and everybody

00:02:46.900 --> 00:02:49.340
on his team to make this record.

00:02:49.340 --> 00:02:52.640
And it just became that
project that you dream about.

00:02:52.640 --> 00:02:57.010
That was something I 100% did
for the journey and the ride.

00:02:57.010 --> 00:03:00.604
And the business end,
we'll make some money.

00:03:00.604 --> 00:03:01.520
We'll lose some money.

00:03:01.520 --> 00:03:04.180
We don't know exactly what's
going to happen there--

00:03:04.180 --> 00:03:06.860
hopefully make some money.

00:03:06.860 --> 00:03:09.350
But if not, we'll be
sleeping on David's couch.

00:03:09.350 --> 00:03:12.060
And you know, it's still
nicer than my house.

00:03:15.200 --> 00:03:17.570
The point is, it's one
of those dream projects.

00:03:17.570 --> 00:03:20.195
It's like, if there's something
you're passionate about-- I was

00:03:20.195 --> 00:03:22.880
passionate about R.E.M. and
The Smiths and Lou Reed and Bob

00:03:22.880 --> 00:03:23.380
Dylan.

00:03:23.380 --> 00:03:25.790
And for me, those are my heroes.

00:03:25.790 --> 00:03:29.030
And then when you see reviews in
"Rolling Stone" about the album

00:03:29.030 --> 00:03:33.330
that's coming out and it says,
sounds like The Cure and R.E.M.

00:03:33.330 --> 00:03:35.800
and Lou Reed and Bob Dylan,
and you're like, wow,

00:03:35.800 --> 00:03:36.860
this is trippy.

00:03:36.860 --> 00:03:40.260
So kind of like the guy
probably that started Google,

00:03:40.260 --> 00:03:42.390
but he made like
a ton more money.

00:03:42.390 --> 00:03:44.910
He had an idea, and that
really panned out well

00:03:44.910 --> 00:03:45.810
for a lot of people.

00:03:45.810 --> 00:03:50.686
So anyways, I want
to introduce David.

00:03:50.686 --> 00:03:51.810
We're going to play a song.

00:03:51.810 --> 00:03:53.726
We're going to play four
tracks off the record

00:03:53.726 --> 00:03:56.470
and then in between, I'm going
to ask a couple questions,

00:03:56.470 --> 00:03:58.261
and we're going to hand
it over to you guys

00:03:58.261 --> 00:04:01.820
to ask questions to David about
what's going on in his life

00:04:01.820 --> 00:04:03.060
and in his career.

00:04:03.060 --> 00:04:07.900
So I just want to thank
quickly the people that

00:04:07.900 --> 00:04:08.820
really helped do this.

00:04:08.820 --> 00:04:13.630
David Flores, Kathleen, Carrie
Lee, the band, of course.

00:04:13.630 --> 00:04:16.532
But me and my friend
were sitting on the couch

00:04:16.532 --> 00:04:17.990
one day watching
"Californication."

00:04:17.990 --> 00:04:20.299
I was like, you work at Google.

00:04:20.299 --> 00:04:21.549
Maybe I'll come by with David.

00:04:21.549 --> 00:04:22.450
Do you think people
would be interested?

00:04:22.450 --> 00:04:23.658
And he's like, oh definitely.

00:04:23.658 --> 00:04:24.450
I'm like, OK, cool.

00:04:24.450 --> 00:04:25.760
So now we're here.

00:04:25.760 --> 00:04:28.350
So that's how it happened.

00:04:28.350 --> 00:04:30.570
But without further
ado, the people

00:04:30.570 --> 00:04:32.420
you really want
to see, the band.

00:04:32.420 --> 00:04:36.054
Colin Lee, Pat McCusker,
and David Duchovny.

00:04:36.054 --> 00:04:37.042
[APPLAUSE]

00:04:46.940 --> 00:04:48.320
DAVID DUCHOVNY: Hi.

00:04:48.320 --> 00:04:51.254
I have this USB thing
that goes in the--

00:04:51.254 --> 00:04:55.520
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:55.520 --> 00:04:57.890
Yeah.

00:04:57.890 --> 00:05:02.140
So these are the stripped down
versions of songs on the album.

00:05:02.140 --> 00:05:05.350
I guess we call them acoustic,
but we seem to be amplified.

00:05:05.350 --> 00:05:06.810
So it's kind of an in between.

00:05:06.810 --> 00:05:11.400
But what are we going
to start with? "3000"?

00:05:11.400 --> 00:05:13.620
It has some New York
geography-- I apologize

00:05:13.620 --> 00:05:15.701
for that-- in this song.

00:05:15.701 --> 00:05:19.660
There's a lot of Central
Park imagery, so forgive me.

00:05:24.151 --> 00:05:26.646
[MUSIC - DAVID DUCHOVNY, "3000"]

00:09:02.178 --> 00:09:04.146
[APPLAUSE]

00:09:12.715 --> 00:09:13.840
BRAD: So, it sounded great.

00:09:13.840 --> 00:09:16.424
It's the second time you've ever
performed in front of people.

00:09:16.424 --> 00:09:18.006
DAVID DUCHOVNY:
That's the happy song.

00:09:18.006 --> 00:09:18.626
BRAD: Yeah.

00:09:18.626 --> 00:09:21.940
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:21.940 --> 00:09:25.930
So it's been definitely
a busy year for you,

00:09:25.930 --> 00:09:29.575
and being part of making
this record was interesting

00:09:29.575 --> 00:09:33.789
because it was the first time
I made an album with-- I don't

00:09:33.789 --> 00:09:35.080
want to say someone like David.

00:09:35.080 --> 00:09:37.590
He's sort of a
unique guy in is own,

00:09:37.590 --> 00:09:40.630
but somebody that's had massive
success on the Hollywood side.

00:09:40.630 --> 00:09:42.495
DAVID DUCHOVNY:
Where'd my band go?

00:09:42.495 --> 00:09:42.780
BRAD: They're done.

00:09:42.780 --> 00:09:43.140
They left.

00:09:43.140 --> 00:09:44.190
DAVID DUCHOVNY: What the hell?

00:09:44.190 --> 00:09:44.720
BRAD: One song.

00:09:44.720 --> 00:09:45.510
DAVID DUCHOVNY: Stay out here.

00:09:45.510 --> 00:09:46.759
We're going to sing some more.

00:09:46.759 --> 00:09:47.560
BRAD: Yeah, Yeah.

00:09:47.560 --> 00:09:47.890
DAVID DUCHOVNY: Yeah.

00:09:47.890 --> 00:09:49.390
BRAD: We have
questions for you too.

00:09:53.820 --> 00:09:57.920
So trying to just schedule
and make this all happen

00:09:57.920 --> 00:10:01.300
was a little bit longer than
making a traditional record.

00:10:01.300 --> 00:10:05.690
But David decided to write a
book in between it all and then

00:10:05.690 --> 00:10:09.330
was coming off filming a new
show for NBC called "Aquarius,"

00:10:09.330 --> 00:10:14.417
which we'll talk about in a
bit, and "X-Files" coming back,

00:10:14.417 --> 00:10:15.250
filming this summer.

00:10:15.250 --> 00:10:18.790
So a lot of stuff going on.

00:10:18.790 --> 00:10:20.180
And we'll get to that too.

00:10:20.180 --> 00:10:26.530
So in terms of writing an
album, it's a very real record.

00:10:26.530 --> 00:10:28.620
Can you talk a little
bit about the process

00:10:28.620 --> 00:10:30.900
of actually making the music?

00:10:30.900 --> 00:10:32.470
Like, how these
songs came to you.

00:10:32.470 --> 00:10:36.020
Is this a collection of
thoughts over years of time?

00:10:36.020 --> 00:10:37.290
Is it a certain period?

00:10:37.290 --> 00:10:40.270
And just taking the jump from
the Hollywood side to say I'm

00:10:40.270 --> 00:10:42.250
going to really write songs.

00:10:42.250 --> 00:10:45.520
DAVID DUCHOVNY:
Well, it's a-- yeah,

00:10:45.520 --> 00:10:46.980
I guess it's a certain period.

00:10:46.980 --> 00:10:51.940
All the songs have a certain
kind of flavor to them,

00:10:51.940 --> 00:10:53.200
I think.

00:10:53.200 --> 00:10:56.560
It's like a snapshot
of a certain time.

00:10:56.560 --> 00:11:02.650
But I think I just
never had an idea

00:11:02.650 --> 00:11:07.640
that I would make an album.

00:11:07.640 --> 00:11:11.000
I have a phone that
records things on it.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.510
You guys might have heard of it.

00:11:13.510 --> 00:11:16.380
OK, I won't do jokes
like that so much.

00:11:16.380 --> 00:11:19.212
I thought they'd go over
better, but they're not

00:11:19.212 --> 00:11:20.170
going over well at all.

00:11:20.170 --> 00:11:23.030
Anyway, so I have
Garage Band on my phone.

00:11:23.030 --> 00:11:25.150
And I just use it
as a tape recorder

00:11:25.150 --> 00:11:27.730
because I can't even figure out
how to do multi-tracks on it.

00:11:27.730 --> 00:11:31.470
And I only play one instrument,
so it doesn't matter.

00:11:31.470 --> 00:11:34.800
So I would just sit there,
and after I figured out

00:11:34.800 --> 00:11:36.630
that there are only so
many chords that you

00:11:36.630 --> 00:11:39.400
can play on guitar,
and in rock and roll

00:11:39.400 --> 00:11:40.650
there are only so many chords.

00:11:40.650 --> 00:11:43.108
And these songs that I like,
there are only so many chords.

00:11:43.108 --> 00:11:45.180
And at some point I
knew most of them.

00:11:45.180 --> 00:11:48.590
So I thought, well, maybe if
I can come up with a melody,

00:11:48.590 --> 00:11:49.610
I can write a song.

00:11:49.610 --> 00:11:50.960
So I started doing that.

00:11:50.960 --> 00:11:53.770
The words for me
were always first

00:11:53.770 --> 00:11:57.690
and always, I don't want
to say easy, but easier.

00:11:57.690 --> 00:12:00.360
And so then I just starting
putting words on the melodies

00:12:00.360 --> 00:12:01.650
and put them on my phone.

00:12:01.650 --> 00:12:03.240
And I thought, oh, I've
written some songs that

00:12:03.240 --> 00:12:03.906
are on my phone.

00:12:03.906 --> 00:12:07.780
I hope nobody finds my phone.

00:12:07.780 --> 00:12:11.250
And then through Keaton
Simons I met Brad.

00:12:11.250 --> 00:12:15.490
And Brad really kept
pushing me to get better,

00:12:15.490 --> 00:12:19.820
and you know, just to
get better and to get

00:12:19.820 --> 00:12:24.239
more serious about recording,
and hooked me up with Colin

00:12:24.239 --> 00:12:25.280
and the rest of the guys.

00:12:25.280 --> 00:12:28.310
And we made it into an album.

00:12:28.310 --> 00:12:30.020
I love the sound of it.

00:12:30.020 --> 00:12:34.140
I can't believe
that I'm part of it.

00:12:34.140 --> 00:12:36.750
It's the weirdest feeling.

00:12:36.750 --> 00:12:38.090
I'm not sure it's real.

00:12:38.090 --> 00:12:41.540
But he showed me
the physical box.

00:12:41.540 --> 00:12:42.764
You got the box?

00:12:42.764 --> 00:12:44.430
BRAD: Carrie, do we
have that somewhere?

00:12:44.430 --> 00:12:45.080
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:45.080 --> 00:12:46.538
DAVID DUCHOVNY:
Today, this morning

00:12:46.538 --> 00:12:49.230
was the first time I saw it
and I was like, give me that.

00:12:49.230 --> 00:12:51.625
BRAD: It's probably in my bag.

00:12:51.625 --> 00:12:53.500
DAVID DUCHOVNY: I didn't
answer any question,

00:12:53.500 --> 00:12:54.635
but I said some things.

00:12:54.635 --> 00:12:55.135
BRAD: Yeah.

00:12:57.580 --> 00:13:00.180
Well, I think one of the
things that stood out

00:13:00.180 --> 00:13:03.530
to me most in this project is--

00:13:03.530 --> 00:13:05.169
DAVID DUCHOVNY: Why
isn't it in my bag?

00:13:05.169 --> 00:13:06.085
Why is it in that bag?

00:13:06.085 --> 00:13:07.540
It should be in my bag.

00:13:07.540 --> 00:13:09.906
BRAD: That's only the proof.

00:13:09.906 --> 00:13:12.684
It's not even out yet.

00:13:12.684 --> 00:13:14.100
I think it's in
the middle pocket.

00:13:14.100 --> 00:13:16.433
DAVID DUCHOVNY: For instance,
"Hell or Highwater," which

00:13:16.433 --> 00:13:19.950
is the single, Brad loves that
song, and he would not stop.

00:13:19.950 --> 00:13:23.196
He's just such a
pain in the ass.

00:13:23.196 --> 00:13:25.600
You know, I only have my voice.

00:13:25.600 --> 00:13:28.790
You know, it's a
small instrument.

00:13:28.790 --> 00:13:34.090
And Brad was like, sing
better, sing better.

00:13:34.090 --> 00:13:34.710
And I hated--

00:13:34.710 --> 00:13:37.020
BRAD: Not exactly like that.

00:13:37.020 --> 00:13:39.842
DAVID DUCHOVNY: No,
he's very encouraging.

00:13:39.842 --> 00:13:40.670
No.

00:13:40.670 --> 00:13:43.160
That didn't sound-- I sounded
like I was being ironic.

00:13:43.160 --> 00:13:45.750
But he's actually
a total enthusiast

00:13:45.750 --> 00:13:48.430
and makes a lot
of stuff possible.

00:13:48.430 --> 00:13:50.990
He's one of those guys that
tells you it can be done,

00:13:50.990 --> 00:13:52.620
which is rare.

00:13:52.620 --> 00:13:53.910
Most people tell you it can't.

00:13:56.700 --> 00:14:01.330
But even so, he was a real pain
in the ass about that song.

00:14:01.330 --> 00:14:04.310
And we finally got
it last winter.

00:14:04.310 --> 00:14:07.277
Look at that thing.

00:14:07.277 --> 00:14:08.860
BRAD: Tell them about
the album cover.

00:14:08.860 --> 00:14:10.235
DAVID DUCHOVNY:
It's upside down.

00:14:10.235 --> 00:14:11.412
[APPLAUSE]

00:14:15.160 --> 00:14:16.230
Anyway, so more--

00:14:16.230 --> 00:14:19.240
BRAD: Tell them about
the album cover.

00:14:19.240 --> 00:14:21.115
DAVID DUCHOVNY: There's
a camera on my phone.

00:14:23.790 --> 00:14:25.270
And I took that picture.

00:14:25.270 --> 00:14:28.520
I was down vacationing
with my kids

00:14:28.520 --> 00:14:30.999
and it's just a reflection.

00:14:30.999 --> 00:14:32.290
I was taking a picture of them.

00:14:32.290 --> 00:14:33.081
You can't see them.

00:14:33.081 --> 00:14:35.190
They're in the room,
and you only see me.

00:14:35.190 --> 00:14:37.250
But it's not important.

00:14:37.250 --> 00:14:39.880
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:39.880 --> 00:14:42.140
BRAD: I think the import
part of the picture

00:14:42.140 --> 00:14:44.940
of that is we would often
practice in David's living

00:14:44.940 --> 00:14:45.540
room.

00:14:45.540 --> 00:14:47.165
And then through the
months and months,

00:14:47.165 --> 00:14:48.740
you're thinking
about art and how

00:14:48.740 --> 00:14:50.810
you want to market the
record, and et cetera.

00:14:50.810 --> 00:14:53.059
And I always love kind of
the black and white imagery,

00:14:53.059 --> 00:14:53.960
we all kind of did.

00:14:53.960 --> 00:14:56.435
And then coming up with the
album cover took forever,

00:14:56.435 --> 00:14:58.560
and finally we were like,
wait, this picture that's

00:14:58.560 --> 00:15:00.610
been hanging above us while
we've been making this album,

00:15:00.610 --> 00:15:01.560
let's just use that.

00:15:01.560 --> 00:15:02.930
And that's how it came together.

00:15:02.930 --> 00:15:05.054
DAVID DUCHOVNY: And it was
cheap because I took it.

00:15:05.054 --> 00:15:06.250
BRAD: And it was cheap.

00:15:06.250 --> 00:15:08.080
Yeah, exactly.

00:15:08.080 --> 00:15:10.245
OK, let's hear another song.

00:15:16.601 --> 00:15:18.476
DAVID DUCHOVNY: This is
called "Let it Rain."

00:15:18.476 --> 00:15:20.408
There's a lot of
rain on the album.

00:15:20.408 --> 00:15:23.789
[MUSIC DAVID DUCHOVNY, "LET IT
 RAIN"]

00:20:04.563 --> 00:20:06.551
[APPLAUSE]

00:20:13.020 --> 00:20:14.400
BRAD: That sounds great.

00:20:14.400 --> 00:20:16.880
Like David said, I'm
a bit of a miser when

00:20:16.880 --> 00:20:20.170
it comes to the sound, so
when it sounds perfect,

00:20:20.170 --> 00:20:23.587
I'm that one weird guy that's
like, no, one more time.

00:20:23.587 --> 00:20:25.670
And then that's like six
hours later, you're like,

00:20:25.670 --> 00:20:26.284
OK, we got it.

00:20:26.284 --> 00:20:28.450
DAVID DUCHOVNY: You want
me to sing it again, right?

00:20:28.450 --> 00:20:30.080
BRAD: Yeah, exactly.

00:20:30.080 --> 00:20:33.090
But I remember we were in the
studio and starting, and Colin

00:20:33.090 --> 00:20:37.670
Lee here, who is the
producer of the record, Colin

00:20:37.670 --> 00:20:40.770
and I met through
one of the girls who

00:20:40.770 --> 00:20:43.650
works with me, Carrie.

00:20:43.650 --> 00:20:45.250
