00:35:36.000 --> 00:35:37.600
I'm not kidding.

00:35:37.600 --> 00:35:43.050
So when I started talking
to Brad about recording,

00:35:43.050 --> 00:35:46.660
I found a voice teacher
New York, just by chance,

00:35:46.660 --> 00:35:51.160
who was amazing-- is amazing--
a guy named Don Lawrence.

00:35:51.160 --> 00:35:54.350
And in 20 minutes he
had me, not singing,

00:35:54.350 --> 00:35:56.330
but he had me thinking
about singing in a way

00:35:56.330 --> 00:35:58.410
that I'd never thought before.

00:35:58.410 --> 00:36:03.450
And it's amazing when you find
a real teacher, just very lucky.

00:36:03.450 --> 00:36:08.740
And so I've been just practicing
singing for a year now.

00:36:08.740 --> 00:36:10.960
Every day I sing a little bit.

00:36:10.960 --> 00:36:13.022
I do my scales.

00:36:13.022 --> 00:36:14.790
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:14.790 --> 00:36:17.360
DAVID DUCHOVNY: So you know,
that's been the hardest part,

00:36:17.360 --> 00:36:21.420
and just committing to
that and trying to sing.

00:36:21.420 --> 00:36:25.958
It's not me, but here I
am, subjecting you to it.

00:36:25.958 --> 00:36:27.830
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:27.830 --> 00:36:30.650
BRAD: We're going to go
with another question

00:36:30.650 --> 00:36:31.507
from the back right.

00:36:31.507 --> 00:36:32.840
AUDIENCE: Thanks for coming out.

00:36:32.840 --> 00:36:36.680
A quick question that you always
ask people who are into music,

00:36:36.680 --> 00:36:39.360
what have you been
listening to recently?

00:36:39.360 --> 00:36:40.940
Oh, hey, I'm in the light.

00:36:40.940 --> 00:36:43.100
What records have you been
listening to recently?

00:36:43.100 --> 00:36:43.960
Are there any bands?

00:36:43.960 --> 00:36:46.001
We've had a lot of bands
that come out of Boston.

00:36:46.001 --> 00:36:49.220
And just wanted to know what's
been inspiring you recently.

00:36:49.220 --> 00:36:54.200
DAVID DUCHOVNY: I tended not
to listen to music while we've

00:36:54.200 --> 00:36:57.040
been doing the
record, only because I

00:36:57.040 --> 00:37:00.010
find that if I read
when I'm writing,

00:37:00.010 --> 00:37:02.570
I tend to just write
what I'm reading.

00:37:02.570 --> 00:37:03.560
And that's illegal.

00:37:03.560 --> 00:37:08.390
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:11.310 --> 00:37:14.580
So I haven't really
been listening,

00:37:14.580 --> 00:37:18.630
but historically, I'm just
like a '60s, '70s guy.

00:37:18.630 --> 00:37:22.460
Straight ahead rock and roll,
British invasion, Beatles,

00:37:22.460 --> 00:37:25.050
Stones, Who, Zeppelin.

00:37:25.050 --> 00:37:28.840
But then I go to Tom Petty,
and I love Dylan and Wilco.

00:37:31.620 --> 00:37:33.290
R.E.M I love.

00:37:33.290 --> 00:37:36.680
I love a lot of
different kinds of music.

00:37:36.680 --> 00:37:39.382
BRAD: Your kids, you know
all the modern stuff too.

00:37:39.382 --> 00:37:40.840
Like, we were
hanging out yesterday

00:37:40.840 --> 00:37:42.548
and you were like this
is Arctic Monkeys.

00:37:42.548 --> 00:37:43.310
I love this band.

00:37:43.310 --> 00:37:43.970
And I was like, what?

00:37:43.970 --> 00:37:45.031
DAVID DUCHOVNY: Yeah, I'm hip.

00:37:45.031 --> 00:37:45.531
I'm hip.

00:37:45.531 --> 00:37:47.980
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:47.980 --> 00:37:51.200
I like Electric Field by MGMT.

00:37:51.200 --> 00:37:51.931
How old is that?

00:37:51.931 --> 00:37:52.930
It's already old, right?

00:37:52.930 --> 00:37:54.890
But I like it.

00:37:54.890 --> 00:37:55.860
You don't know it?

00:37:55.860 --> 00:37:56.640
Yeah, you know it.

00:37:56.640 --> 00:37:58.190
That's good groove, right?

00:37:58.190 --> 00:37:58.770
Next time.

00:37:58.770 --> 00:38:02.342
Next time, we'll do that.

00:38:02.342 --> 00:38:03.300
BRAD: Another question.

00:38:10.320 --> 00:38:13.990
Here we go, on the left.

00:38:13.990 --> 00:38:18.030
I think she's going
to bring the mic over.

00:38:18.030 --> 00:38:19.224
AUDIENCE: Oh, I'm Ed.

00:38:19.224 --> 00:38:20.140
DAVID DUCHOVNY: Hi Ed.

00:38:20.140 --> 00:38:22.865
AUDIENCE: I was listening to
the lyrics on your first song

00:38:22.865 --> 00:38:24.660
that you played and
I was wondering,

00:38:24.660 --> 00:38:26.790
do you wear a Fitbit?

00:38:26.790 --> 00:38:29.760
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:31.035 --> 00:38:32.910
Just because we have a
step competition here.

00:38:32.910 --> 00:38:33.410
So.

00:38:33.410 --> 00:38:35.046
Yeah.

00:38:35.046 --> 00:38:36.934
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:40.515 --> 00:38:42.390
DAVID DUCHOVNY: I'm
going to go out on a limb

00:38:42.390 --> 00:38:47.515
and say only at Google will I
be asked that question, I hope.

00:38:50.030 --> 00:38:54.840
It's funny because
just last weekend I

00:38:54.840 --> 00:38:57.240
made the journey of which
I was writing about.

00:38:57.240 --> 00:39:00.200
And I was like, I'm
going to count the steps.

00:39:00.200 --> 00:39:02.650
And I kept on getting lost.

00:39:02.650 --> 00:39:05.530
I had hundreds on my fingers.

00:39:05.530 --> 00:39:07.870
I do not have Fitbit.

00:39:07.870 --> 00:39:09.930
So I'm so old school.

00:39:09.930 --> 00:39:12.500
As they said in
Larry Sanders, they

00:39:12.500 --> 00:39:17.140
tore down my school to
build the old school.

00:39:17.140 --> 00:39:21.580
So I was like 100,
400, 500, 1,000.

00:39:21.580 --> 00:39:24.860
It was about, it was in
the neighborhood of 3,000.

00:39:24.860 --> 00:39:28.054
It might have been
a little less.

00:39:28.054 --> 00:39:31.360
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:31.360 --> 00:39:36.920
But the chorus doesn't
sound as good as 2,796.

00:39:36.920 --> 00:39:40.580
2,796.

00:39:40.580 --> 00:39:44.610
BRAD: I think we have
another one up here.

00:39:44.610 --> 00:39:46.120
AUDIENCE: Hi, I'm Bertha.

00:39:46.120 --> 00:39:48.480
I'm also writing
music right now.

00:39:48.480 --> 00:39:51.390
So what's your music
writing process?

00:39:51.390 --> 00:39:55.659
DAVID DUCHOVNY: It was
just whenever it happened.

00:39:55.659 --> 00:39:57.950
I mean, I'd sit down, and
I'd start playing the guitar.

00:39:57.950 --> 00:40:00.910
And I would have like
three or four chords

00:40:00.910 --> 00:40:02.550
that I liked the way
they fit together.

00:40:02.550 --> 00:40:05.570
And then and then
I would just maybe

00:40:05.570 --> 00:40:07.140
hear a melody on top of that.

00:40:07.140 --> 00:40:09.480
And then the words
were just easy.

00:40:09.480 --> 00:40:15.570
I mean, I had a booklet of
thoughts more than words.

00:40:15.570 --> 00:40:20.140
And that's it, just kind
all at the same time

00:40:20.140 --> 00:40:21.561
rather than one
before the other.

00:40:21.561 --> 00:40:23.560
But I would say the chords
and the melody first.

00:40:23.560 --> 00:40:27.070
And then lyrically, I never
worry about the lyrics coming.

00:40:27.070 --> 00:40:31.440
It was really, will I ever
think of another melody?

00:40:31.440 --> 00:40:32.310
And I'm not sure.

00:40:35.466 --> 00:40:36.590
BRAD: There's one up front.

00:40:36.590 --> 00:40:37.631
DAVID DUCHOVNY: A ringer.

00:40:37.631 --> 00:40:39.530
We have a ringer in the house.

00:40:39.530 --> 00:40:42.540
Full disclosure
before the question.

00:40:42.540 --> 00:40:43.207
Full disclosure.

00:40:43.207 --> 00:40:44.289
AUDIENCE: Full disclosure.

00:40:44.289 --> 00:40:45.152
We're related.

00:40:47.840 --> 00:40:50.640
So how do your kids
feel about Dad suddenly

00:40:50.640 --> 00:40:53.135
becoming a rock star?

00:40:53.135 --> 00:40:54.635
DAVID DUCHOVNY:
They're embarrassed.

00:40:57.726 --> 00:41:00.250
Yeah, they're like
making believe

00:41:00.250 --> 00:41:01.520
it's not happening at all.

00:41:01.520 --> 00:41:02.320
I'm sure they are.

00:41:02.320 --> 00:41:05.390
I mean, they have not
asked to hear anything.

00:41:08.340 --> 00:41:10.620
And I do have a concert.

00:41:10.620 --> 00:41:13.680
We have the album release
concert next week in New York,

00:41:13.680 --> 00:41:18.600
and I've not invited them.

00:41:18.600 --> 00:41:19.240
It's late.

00:41:19.240 --> 00:41:21.950
It's past their bedtime.

00:41:21.950 --> 00:41:24.800
It's funny.

00:41:24.800 --> 00:41:29.630
I can only think
and hope that they

00:41:29.630 --> 00:41:32.150
get exactly what I wanted
them to get out of it, which

00:41:32.150 --> 00:41:35.890
was just like, just try things.

00:41:35.890 --> 00:41:40.560
I think, because they would
do-- play a little something.

00:41:40.560 --> 00:41:43.015
This is how they react to it.

00:41:43.015 --> 00:41:45.430
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:48.330 --> 00:41:51.982
So that's what I get from them.

00:41:51.982 --> 00:41:53.690
BRAD: It is funny,
because sometimes we'd

00:41:53.690 --> 00:41:54.690
play at your house.

00:41:54.690 --> 00:41:56.180
It's like 100% music.

00:41:56.180 --> 00:41:58.510
And then when your kids
come home, it's 0% music.

00:41:58.510 --> 00:42:01.230
It's like we don't talk
about it in front of them.

00:42:01.230 --> 00:42:02.780
It's its own entity.

00:42:02.780 --> 00:42:04.280
DAVID DUCHOVNY:
It's a dirty secret.

00:42:04.280 --> 00:42:05.812
BRAD: Yeah.

00:42:05.812 --> 00:42:07.520
We have one more
question, then will do--

00:42:07.520 --> 00:42:09.770
DAVID DUCHOVNY: I do have
one song that's specifically

00:42:09.770 --> 00:42:11.420
for West called
"Stay on the Train"

00:42:11.420 --> 00:42:12.777
that we won't be doing here.

00:42:12.777 --> 00:42:14.360
BRAD: You're not
going to play at all?

00:42:14.360 --> 00:42:15.590
DAVID DUCHOVNY:
Unless you want to.

00:42:15.590 --> 00:42:16.910
BRAD: No, I think we
should do "Hell" maybe.

00:42:16.910 --> 00:42:17.480
DAVID DUCHOVNY: Oh,
you want to do "Hell"?

00:42:17.480 --> 00:42:17.990
OK.

00:42:17.990 --> 00:42:20.190
BRAD: But lets see
if we can do one more

00:42:20.190 --> 00:42:23.850
question, or a final question,
before the last song.

00:42:23.850 --> 00:42:27.210
Right up front here
on the right, or both.

00:42:27.210 --> 00:42:29.057
We'll do two more.

00:42:29.057 --> 00:42:29.890
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:42:29.890 --> 00:42:30.480
Hi, I'm Libby.

00:42:30.480 --> 00:42:34.305
DAVID DUCHOVNY: Can I
get a Fitbit for free?

00:42:34.305 --> 00:42:37.570
Can I get one for free?

00:42:37.570 --> 00:42:38.890
If you show me how to use it.

00:42:38.890 --> 00:42:40.617
Where do I put it?

00:42:40.617 --> 00:42:41.730
On my foot?

00:42:41.730 --> 00:42:43.110
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:43.110 --> 00:42:44.480
On your belt.

00:42:44.480 --> 00:42:46.750
BRAD: You've got to
Google this stuff, man.

00:42:46.750 --> 00:42:48.240
DAVID DUCHOVNY:
How does it know?

00:42:48.240 --> 00:42:50.060
That's incredible.

00:42:50.060 --> 00:42:52.127
I want a Fitbit.

00:42:52.127 --> 00:42:52.626
Huh?

00:42:55.340 --> 00:42:57.680
All hell's breaking loose now.

00:42:57.680 --> 00:42:58.750
All right.

00:42:58.750 --> 00:42:59.250
Where?

00:42:59.250 --> 00:43:01.440
BRAD: OK, we'll go to the
last question and then

00:43:01.440 --> 00:43:02.657
the final song.

00:43:02.657 --> 00:43:03.490
AUDIENCE: I'm Libby.

00:43:03.490 --> 00:43:06.440
I don't have a Fitbit.

00:43:06.440 --> 00:43:09.990
And so being a creative
person-- acting,

00:43:09.990 --> 00:43:13.100
and writing, and
now doing music--

00:43:13.100 --> 00:43:16.159
is there one, at this
particular moment,

00:43:16.159 --> 00:43:18.075
I'm sure that the singing
is, but is there one

00:43:18.075 --> 00:43:21.670
that you're surprised or
that really kind of fills

00:43:21.670 --> 00:43:23.970
your soul in a way that you
didn't really expect it to?

00:43:27.339 --> 00:43:28.130
DAVID DUCHOVNY: No.

00:43:28.130 --> 00:43:30.760
I think they all do something.

00:43:30.760 --> 00:43:35.300
I mean, I feel like
just an expressive

00:43:35.300 --> 00:43:38.100
person, like I'm just
trying to express something.

00:43:38.100 --> 00:43:42.580
And I'm having an image
right now of the cake thing

00:43:42.580 --> 00:43:46.470
when you squeeze the icing,
and it's different size nozzle

00:43:46.470 --> 00:43:47.450
sometimes.

00:43:47.450 --> 00:43:49.530
So that's gross.

00:43:49.530 --> 00:43:51.850
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:51.850 --> 00:43:54.430
So I guess that's the
way I feel I feel about.

00:43:58.130 --> 00:44:00.690
I just try to stay
creative, and try

00:44:00.690 --> 00:44:06.020
to stay-- whoa-- try to
stay alive and growing

00:44:06.020 --> 00:44:07.380
and challenged.

00:44:07.380 --> 00:44:11.386
And challenged, I
try to be challenged.

00:44:11.386 --> 00:44:15.960
You know, someone was asking me
yesterday, challenging myself.

00:44:15.960 --> 00:44:17.460
And I was like,
well, maybe it would

00:44:17.460 --> 00:44:19.287
be nice to not be challenged.

00:44:19.287 --> 00:44:21.370
Maybe it would be nice to
just relax a little bit.

00:44:21.370 --> 00:44:24.120
But apparently that's
not what I'm into.

00:44:24.120 --> 00:44:26.690
So that's all.

00:44:26.690 --> 00:44:27.800
I don't know.

00:44:27.800 --> 00:44:29.110
I love directing too.

00:44:29.110 --> 00:44:32.020
I haven't done much
of that recently.

00:44:32.020 --> 00:44:34.790
I like sitting in the
dark yelling instructions.

00:44:34.790 --> 00:44:36.234
[LAUGHTER]

00:44:36.234 --> 00:44:38.900
BRAD: So this is going to be the
last song, "Hell or Highwater."

00:44:38.900 --> 00:44:41.274
And then after the song if
everyone wants to stay seated,

00:44:41.274 --> 00:44:45.010
we'll do the group selfie shot.

00:44:45.010 --> 00:44:46.480
And thank everybody again.

00:44:46.480 --> 00:44:48.760
But this is the single,
"Hell or Highwater."

00:44:48.760 --> 00:44:51.380
DAVID DUCHOVNY: Thank you,
and thanks for coming out

00:44:51.380 --> 00:44:54.710
and being here, because, really,
this is like rehearsal for us.

00:44:54.710 --> 00:44:57.240
So it's great.

00:44:57.240 --> 00:44:59.230
Thank you for the
opportunity to rehearse

00:44:59.230 --> 00:45:03.155
with your lovely sound system.

00:45:03.155 --> 00:45:06.550
[MUSIC DAVID DUCHOVNY, "HELL OR
 HIGHWATER"]

00:50:37.344 --> 00:50:38.350
[APPLAUSE]

00:50:38.350 --> 00:50:40.250
DAVID DUCHOVNY: Thank you.

